WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.637 --> 00:00:01.583
What am I doing?

00:00:01.583 --> 00:00:03.150
We're just, we're gonna,
I'm just gonna listen to you

00:00:03.150 --> 00:00:04.830
and I'm just gonna go like this and smile.

00:00:04.830 --> 00:00:07.500
Hi everyone. I'm sitting
here with the governor.

00:00:07.500 --> 00:00:11.370
Let, let's just start over.
Hi, everyone. Happy holidays.

00:00:11.370 --> 00:00:12.370
We, you are.

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:15.450
Nope. Do it again. Number three,

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:19.020
The Newsom are having a moment.

00:00:19.020 --> 00:00:20.285
2028, woo

00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:24.540
Though America's next presidential
election is still more

00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:25.800
than two years away,

00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:28.710
the betting pools show
California Governor Gavin Newsom

00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:30.360
ahead of the Democratic pack.

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:34.830
In a political era of big
singular personalities,

00:00:34.830 --> 00:00:36.630
Newsom fits the mold.

00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:39.870
Good to see you
Telegenic, tactical

00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:41.580
and polarizing capable

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:44.100
of inspiring both passion and contempt.

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:45.840
Gavin Newscum is incompetent,

00:00:47.070 --> 00:00:50.010
But there's nothing
singular about this operation.

00:00:50.010 --> 00:00:53.400
More often than not, his
teammate, Jennifer Siebel Newsom,

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:55.230
is in the room where it happens.

00:00:55.230 --> 00:00:56.760
How do you guys decide when to team up?

00:00:56.760 --> 00:00:59.340
She decides
I'm traveling

00:00:59.340 --> 00:01:01.800
with California's first
couple to see what they make

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:03.510
of tech's turn to the right.

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:08.370
I just feel like a lot of
people are losing their way,

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:10.770
Taking on the most
powerful man in the world.

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:13.020
You've dressed him like
Marie Antoinette told him

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:14.250
to take dementia meds.

00:01:14.250 --> 00:01:16.350
You're wincing a little.
I know, it's, I, I,

00:01:16.350 --> 00:01:17.350
I, it's unbecoming.

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:19.470
I should wash my mouth out with soap

00:01:19.470 --> 00:01:22.200
And getting a glimpse of
home life with the Newsoms.

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:23.670
Are you competitive with each other?

00:01:23.670 --> 00:01:25.590
Totally. I beat him in
free throws the other day.

00:01:25.590 --> 00:01:29.190
Thank you very much. I was
asking who puts the hammer down?

00:01:29.190 --> 00:01:31.230
I was a little loose, so
what do you think? I said

00:01:31.230 --> 00:01:33.570
That Jen basically calls the shots.

00:01:36.210 --> 00:01:37.980
I'm all about partnership.

00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:39.725
That was definitely
the right answer then.

00:01:45.785 --> 00:01:46.885
How have you
handled the

00:01:46.885 --> 00:01:47.910
pressure?

00:01:47.910 --> 00:01:51.120
I come here, I come here
with my girlfriends.

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:53.010
I come here with my colleagues.

00:01:53.010 --> 00:01:54.420
I come here with just the dogs

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:59.130
For the Newsoms partnership
begins at home across the

00:01:59.130 --> 00:02:01.500
bridge from San Francisco
in Marin County, known

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:05.040
for its pricey real estate and
spectacular natural beauty.

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:06.960
It's where Jennifer grew up and where she

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:09.150
and the governor have
put down their own roots

00:02:09.150 --> 00:02:10.470
raising four children.

00:02:10.470 --> 00:02:11.760
I heard your, you're a
state park nerd.

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:13.950
I've, I've been watching your Instagram.

00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:15.060
I've seen your walks.

00:02:15.060 --> 00:02:17.250
I, yes. Well, I mean,
come around your shine.

00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:19.650
I'm always like, all right, let's go.

00:02:19.650 --> 00:02:22.830
People love to hate on California.

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:26.550
Look, it's a state of dreamers
and doers and entrepreneurs

00:02:26.550 --> 00:02:30.630
and noble laureates, the
center of manufacturing.

00:02:30.630 --> 00:02:34.230
We produce a third of
the nation's vegetables.

00:02:34.230 --> 00:02:37.140
You know, we've got Silicon
Valley and Hollywood here,

00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:40.020
and so I like to think
there's probably some jealousy

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:42.840
Who wouldn't wanna live here?

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:44.340
It's pretty special.

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:48.060
Of course, there are
those who disagree, those

00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:49.470
who look past the good weather

00:02:49.470 --> 00:02:52.860
and see California as an
intractable tangle of economic

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:54.510
and social problems

00:02:54.510 --> 00:02:57.420
and place much of the
blame with Governor Newsom.

00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:59.245
Hello. How are you? Good to see you again.

00:02:59.245 --> 00:03:01.120
Is this part of the
interview? Are we being happy?

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:02.205
You know, what is this part of it?

00:03:02.205 --> 00:03:04.630
It, it's the always on era.
There's always a hot mic around.

00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:08.110
Gavin Newsom has been a
fixture of California politics

00:03:08.110 --> 00:03:11.470
for more than 20 years
as San Francisco's mayor,

00:03:11.470 --> 00:03:14.320
Lieutenant Governor, and now governor.

00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:16.030
But increasingly, he's become the face

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:19.450
of political opposition to
President Trump at home.

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:20.890
Donald Trump's government isn't

00:03:20.890 --> 00:03:22.390
protecting our communities.

00:03:22.390 --> 00:03:24.430
They're traumatizing our communities

00:03:24.430 --> 00:03:25.430
And abroad.

00:03:25.430 --> 00:03:29.110
He's a T-Rex.
You mate with him or he devours you,

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:31.270
And the president has taken notice.

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:33.550
Look at the job he's
doing in California.

00:03:33.550 --> 00:03:35.590
He's destroying one of our great states.

00:03:35.590 --> 00:03:37.150
In 2025, the state

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:40.300
of California filed more than
50 federal lawsuits against

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:41.830
the Trump administration

00:03:41.830 --> 00:03:45.490
and won a major victory with
the passage of Proposition 50.

00:03:45.490 --> 00:03:46.810
A redistricting measure meant

00:03:46.810 --> 00:03:50.020
to counter similar Republican
efforts urged by Trump ahead

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:51.880
of the 2026 midterms.

00:03:51.880 --> 00:03:55.420
You have a history of taking
up positions that carry a lot

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:58.150
of political risk, same sex marriage,

00:03:58.150 --> 00:04:01.810
environmental regulation,
prop 50, trolling Trump.

00:04:01.810 --> 00:04:03.550
You're out there experimenting.

00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:05.680
Yeah.
What is driving you right now?

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:08.560
Is it ambition or is it outrage?

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:10.570
Well, I, yeah, with
the two driving forces

00:04:10.570 --> 00:04:11.800
of life inspiration

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:15.220
and desperation, I mean,
been inspired by a lot

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:18.910
of our politicians and by
our politics in the past.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:20.020
I, I'm now on the other side

00:04:20.020 --> 00:04:22.000
of maybe feeling a little more
desperate about the moment

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.900
we're living in the blatant corruption

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:28.630
that is occurring on an
hourly, not just daily basis.

00:04:28.630 --> 00:04:32.770
It, it sickens me in my core
as an American, as a father,

00:04:32.770 --> 00:04:36.160
as a husband, as a guy who I
grew up in, in the Bay Area,

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:39.580
and to watch some of my old
friends participate in that.

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:42.820
I need to be more
accountable to this moment.

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:44.470
Why should people trust you?

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:47.410
I, well, trust me, I mean,
I've been, I am who I am

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:49.960
and I've been a, I've been
an open book for decades

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:52.750
and people that know
me best have elected me

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:54.010
to many offices.

00:04:54.010 --> 00:04:56.140
There was an effort to recall
me in the last three elections

00:04:56.140 --> 00:04:58.960
we've won by margins of 20 plus percent.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:00.460
So, I mean, that issue, I think,

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:04.240
has been substantively addressed
for those that chronicle me

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.630
literally and figuratively,
that know me best in this state

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:09.490
and certainly in the Bay Area.

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:12.790
The person who knows Newsom
best of all, is his wife,

00:05:12.790 --> 00:05:14.500
Jennifer Siebel Newsom,

00:05:14.500 --> 00:05:17.410
who was a vocal ally in the Prop 50 fight.

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:20.080
Voting yes on Prop 50 is saying to Trump

00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:23.290
and his cronies that you
cannot cheat in California.

00:05:23.290 --> 00:05:26.260
You cannot steal our power

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:28.450
and you cannot silence our people.

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:35.980
Thank you for coming. Come in.

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:40.150
Thank you for having us at your
house. I have four kids too.

00:05:40.150 --> 00:05:43.930
Yeah. So I can't, it's fun, huh? It's fun.

00:05:43.930 --> 00:05:47.020
And I can imagine the four
kid energy. A lot of energy.

00:05:47.020 --> 00:05:48.250
A lot of energy. All right.

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:50.740
You wanna be called first partner

00:05:50.740 --> 00:05:52.720
instead of First Lady.

00:05:52.720 --> 00:05:55.060
How are you trying to change
the stereotype of what

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:57.410
it means to be a politician's wife?

00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:00.260
For me, I really wanted
to put out to Californians

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:03.140
that I wanted to partner with
California moms and families

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:07.610
and women and children, and
that I would be their partner,

00:06:07.610 --> 00:06:10.940
and that I also was a
partner to the governor.

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:12.830
I'm the first person that
sees 'em in the morning,

00:06:12.830 --> 00:06:14.330
the last person before bed at night.

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:18.140
We share, you know, our
thoughts, our, our passions,

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:20.990
our concerns for California
and for the world.

00:06:20.990 --> 00:06:22.070
Some partners

00:06:22.070 --> 00:06:24.200
of government leaders
enjoy the opportunity

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:26.240
and the attention that
comes with this position.

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:30.350
Do you enjoy it or has it
taken some getting used to?

00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:31.790
I just am a worker bee.

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:34.100
I think my husband and
I are just worker bees.

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:37.640
I actually don't love the
pomp and circumstance at all.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.740
I wanna roll my sleeves
up and get to work.

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:43.820
How did you feel about her wanting

00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:46.445
to be first partner instead of First Lady?

00:06:46.445 --> 00:06:48.985
I mean, I, I, I'd mixed
feelings candidly. I

00:06:48.985 --> 00:06:49.985
thought you liked
it

00:06:49.985 --> 00:06:52.280
I liked it because I thought
it was the right thing,

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:53.930
but I knew that people would, you know,

00:06:54.890 --> 00:06:56.930
have opinions about it, you know,

00:06:56.930 --> 00:06:59.180
because it's, you know,
these traditional roles

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:01.520
and people have strong
opinions about all that.

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:04.370
Jennifer Siebel Newsom
grew up in Ross, California.

00:07:04.370 --> 00:07:07.760
One of five kids in a
wealthy conservative family.

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:10.730
You used to be a registered
Republican. I was, yep.

00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:12.590
Your parents contributed to Ron DeSantis

00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:13.423
Campaign
For Florida Governor,

00:07:13.423 --> 00:07:14.256
If I may
correct the record, my mom

00:07:16.850 --> 00:07:18.470
and dad were invited to a fundraiser

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:20.240
by a mutual friend in Florida,

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:22.280
which is why they gave
money to Ron DeSantis.

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:23.570
It was, and then,

00:07:23.570 --> 00:07:25.820
and they did not like the
way it was manipulated

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:27.260
by the DeSantis camp.

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:29.630
I was raised in a
conservative household, kind

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:32.120
of Reaganesque household.

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:35.090
I didn't know any different
than to kind of revere Reagan.

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:37.370
I grew up in that generation.

00:07:37.370 --> 00:07:41.300
Then I think I tried to be the
version of Decline to State,

00:07:41.300 --> 00:07:45.260
but went independent instead
and made that mistake just

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:47.600
because I, I wasn't ready
to just jump in just

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:49.610
because he was a Democrat.

00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:52.580
But I, I'm a hundred percent
a progressive Democrat.

00:07:52.580 --> 00:07:55.130
And in terms of my values,

00:07:55.130 --> 00:07:56.930
How does this dynamic
work in your own family?

00:07:56.930 --> 00:07:58.610
Like, what's the conversation like at the

00:07:58.610 --> 00:08:00.290
Thanksgiving table?

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:01.610
Do you talk about politics?

00:08:01.610 --> 00:08:04.700
My mom and dad really respect Gavin.

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:07.280
Gavin is an entrepreneur.
He is a businessman.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:12.280
He is very forward thinking,
very fair, very balanced.

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:16.100
I can be a little feistier in terms of,

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:21.050
I feel a, a real
responsibility to fight for

00:08:21.050 --> 00:08:23.090
and on behalf of women and girls.

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:27.770
Siebel Newsom's childhood
was colored by a tragedy just

00:08:27.770 --> 00:08:30.800
before her seventh birthday
when she was involved in a golf

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:33.260
cart accident that
killed her sister Stacey,

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:35.870
who was eight years old in interviews,

00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:38.120
she's described feeling responsible.

00:08:38.120 --> 00:08:40.340
What was it like growing up
Jennifer Siebel?

00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:46.430
I mean, I really woke
up after my sister died,

00:08:47.420 --> 00:08:52.070
but I also lived with a lot

00:08:52.070 --> 00:08:54.080
of guilt and, and pain.

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:58.590
And the beauty of surviving
that was that there were

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:03.360
so many beautiful moms and older women and

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:07.950
and older sisters who
came in to support me.

00:09:07.950 --> 00:09:11.610
I got through it to come
out on the other side

00:09:11.610 --> 00:09:15.120
and realized that I survived

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:19.230
and have this

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:23.640
opportunity to be of service

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:26.190
and be about more than myself

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:28.260
and try to make a difference in the world

00:09:28.260 --> 00:09:29.260
At school,

00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:31.800
Siebel was driven to Excel, recruited

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:34.200
to play on Stanford's
division one soccer team.

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:37.050
She went on to work with women
in indigenous communities in

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:38.910
Africa and Latin America,

00:09:38.910 --> 00:09:41.610
and then returned to Stanford for her MBA,

00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:44.190
and then she headed to Hollywood.

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:47.085
Betsy Hofstadt? Look at you.

00:09:48.030 --> 00:09:50.280
You were typecast as a trophy wife.

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:52.890
Yes, and is it true that
your agent wanted you to take

00:09:52.890 --> 00:09:55.050
Stanford off your
resume so you wouldn't

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:56.370
seem smart?

00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:59.310
Yes, and to lie about my age,
which I didn't do either.

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:02.790
'cause that's not, you know,
those aren't my values.

00:10:02.790 --> 00:10:05.010
And I was proud of my Stanford MBA

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:06.930
and I was proud of my
Stanford undergraduate degree,

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:09.360
and I didn't wanna pretend
to be someone that I wasn't.

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:11.970
How is what you've learned
over the course of your

00:10:11.970 --> 00:10:16.020
career informing what you
think the government needs

00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:17.550
In the entertainment industry?

00:10:17.550 --> 00:10:19.740
I obviously saw a dearth
of women in positions

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:20.880
of power and influence.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:23.940
I also saw women's voices be silenced

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:26.280
because women weren't
the majority of writers,

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:28.260
directors, and producers.

00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:31.530
And similar to the political world,

00:10:31.530 --> 00:10:34.500
women may be rising in
terms of our numbers

00:10:34.500 --> 00:10:35.520
and representation,

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:39.210
but we don't have the same
women, don't have the same voice

00:10:39.210 --> 00:10:41.430
and power in politics.

00:10:41.430 --> 00:10:44.130
She poured her efforts
into advocating for change,

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:45.990
becoming a documentary filmmaker,

00:10:45.990 --> 00:10:48.300
and exploring social issues around gender

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:49.680
and economic inequality.

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:52.530
And she went on to advocate

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:56.100
for herself making headlines
in a California courtroom.

00:10:56.100 --> 00:10:58.955
You testified that Harvey
Weinstein sexually assaulted you.

00:10:58.955 --> 00:11:00.960
Yeah. And you were part
of the Me Too movement,

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:04.770
and there was that moment for women where

00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:07.170
it felt like progress was being made.

00:11:07.170 --> 00:11:09.540
And then there's the
moment that we're in now

00:11:09.540 --> 00:11:13.590
where it feels like so
many things women fought

00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:15.540
for are slipping away.

00:11:15.540 --> 00:11:18.390
Yeah.
How do you make sense of this moment?

00:11:18.390 --> 00:11:20.640
Every time we make progress,

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:23.040
there's another backlash,
I would say there.

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:25.200
Technology is the new backlash.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:30.060
You, we don't have as many
women in power starting,

00:11:30.060 --> 00:11:34.590
designing, running these tech companies.

00:11:34.590 --> 00:11:35.700
The other part of the problem is

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:40.320
that these tech titans are
profiting off of misinformation

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:43.410
and disinformation that
is dividing our country.

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:46.470
It's like ka ka ka kaching with all

00:11:46.470 --> 00:11:48.960
of this misinformation and hate.

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:51.270
It's not who we are as human beings.

00:11:51.270 --> 00:11:53.980
It, it is not what we are as Americans.

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:57.430
It alarms me that we've
gotten to this place

00:11:57.430 --> 00:11:58.720
and that we've allowed it

00:11:59.650 --> 00:12:01.180
To change the balance of power.

00:12:01.180 --> 00:12:03.070
The Newsom's have spearheaded a slate

00:12:03.070 --> 00:12:06.310
of progressive initiatives,
many centered on the wellbeing

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:09.790
of women and families.
Here at the First Partners

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:10.870
Gender equity summit,

